Official of St. Andrews and to the Archdeacon of Dumblane to induet him into the possession of the said deanery accordingly. Dated at St. Peter's, at Rome, in the eighth year of the Pope's consecration‚ 8th October, 1454.

Prosentation, in like manner, by Pope Nicolas V. in favour of Hugh de Douglas‚ a clerk of the diocese of St. Andrews‚ and of noble race by both parents, to a canonry in the church of Brechin and the prebend of Guthen therein, with their revenues not exceeding six pounds sterling yearly, which the Pope had reserved to his own collation in the event of their being resigned by the foresaid William Forbes on his attaining the deanery of the said church‚ because they could not be held in conjunction therewith. Dated at St. Peter’s, at Rome, 8th October, in the eighth year of the Pope's pontificate‚ 1454.

Confirmatio Indulgentie Gilberto Forstar archidiacono Brechinensi .

Galistus III. 616. ad futuram rei memoriam . Rationi congruit et convenit honestati, ut ea que de Romani Pontificis gratia processerunt, licet ejus super- veniente obitu litere apostolice confecte non fuerint super illis, suum tamen consequantur effectum . Dudum siquidem . . . Eugenius Papa quartus pre- decessor noster . . . Gilbertum Forstar, archidiaconum ecclesie Brechinensis‚ in artibus magistrum, de nobili baronum genere procreatum, in suurn et Sedis Apostolice recepit accolitum, sibique diversa priuilegia ac protectionem specialem sedis predicte ex certis causis, tam pro se quam familiaribus beneficiis rebus 61 bonis suis, 61 indulta concessit aliaque fecit, prout in literis desuper confectis plenius continentur . Et deinde . Nicolao Pape V. etiam predecessori nostro pro parte dicti Gilberti exposito, quod ipse contra tenores et effectus dictarum literarum et concessionem dubitabat se tempore procedente . . . molestari posse, et pro parte tunc dicti Gilberti prefato Nicholao predecessori humiliter supplicato, ut priuilegiis exemptionibus et indultis . . . predictis . . . pro eorum subsistentia firmiori robur apostolice confirmationis adjicere . . .
